Access relationship
(Component reads/writes (denoted by arrow) the artefact/data)
System sotware provides "technical" or non-interactive functions
Composition relationship (All of one component makes up part of the other)
Logical or physical environment hosting system software

Represents the files stored on a server.
This can be data storage or configuration and installation.
Includes the "specialisations": - «Directory», - «Database», - «Software», - «Operating System»
Realisation relationship (One component implements or realises the other)
Physical location hosting infrastructure
User accessible application, program or system.
Functionality presented by an application.
Serving relationship (One component used by another)
Interface used to access a service
Data entity used by an application

Flow relationship
(Data flow from one component to another)

Assigned relationship
(One component has ownership or responsibility for another)

ArchiMate 3.1
Language uses a "consistent" set of icons to represent concepts across all layers of architecture, Business, Data, Application and Technology.
E.g. Process, Service, Interface and Function icons are repeated in multiple layers.
A series of steps which produces an outcome
A requirement that must be met by this architecture.
A highlighted assesment of the architecture.
A guiding principle that this architecture adheres to.
Influence relationship, +ve or -ve
A snapshot of the architecture at a point in time, generally Baseline, Target or a Transition.
A work package to be completed to deliver the architecture.
The deliverable of a Work Package.
An asset owned by the Organisation, could be a department, brand, finacial, etc.
A Capability is something that the Organisation does.
A sequence of capabilities which delivers value for the organisation
